body:
If you want to retrieve metadata from your MongoDB Search query, you can apply one of the following configurations
to choose between the [count](count-ref) or [faceted navigation](fts-facet-ref) type of metadata results document:

**Count-option:**

Count Metadata

To return the total or lower-bounded count of your search results, set the [count](count-ref) option in your aggregation stage.

The [$searchMeta](pipe.$searchMeta) stage returns the `count` metadata results, while the [$search](pipe.$search) stage stores the metadata results in the
[$$SEARCH\_META aggregation variable](fts-aggregation-variable) and returns only the search results.
For an example of how to retrieve the `count` metadata results from the `$$SEARCH_META` variable, see [Count Results](count-results).

```json
{
  "$search" | "$searchMeta": {
    "<operator-name>": {
      <operator-specifications>
    },
    "count": {
      "type": "lowerBound" | "total",
      "threshold": <number-of-documents> // Optional
    }
  }
}
```

**Facet-collector:**

Facet Metadata

To run a facet query, which groups results by values or ranges and returns the count for each of these groups,
use the [faceted navigation](fts-facet-ref) collector in your aggregation stage.

The [$searchMeta](pipe.$searchMeta) stage returns `facet` metadata results, while the [$search](pipe.$search) stage stores the metadata results in the
[$$SEARCH\_META aggregation variable](fts-aggregation-variable) and returns only the search results.
For an example of how to retrieve the `facet` metadata results from the `$$SEARCH_META` variable, see [Facet Results](fts-facet-results).

```json
{
  "$search" | "$searchMeta": {
    "facet": {
      "facets": {
        <facet-definitions>
      }
    }
  }
}
```
